Zou Shuang Photo: Courtesy of Xia QiongThe winners of the International Opera Awards, opera's answer to the Oscars, were announced at a ceremony held in London on April 29.  The annual gala ceremony aims to honor outstanding achievements on the stage, backstage and in the pit with awards like Singer of the Year, Opera Company of the Year and the annual Lifetime Achievement Award as well as Awards for Young Singer and Newcomer. Founded by opera lover and philanthropist Harry Hyman in 2012, the Awards exist not only to celebrate established stars, but to support the next generation of talent.  Although young Chinese opera director Zou Shuang was nominated for the Newcomer award, the first Chinese director to be so recognized, she lost the honor to Russian conductor Maxim Emelyanychev that night. Zou is well-known in opera circles for her innovative and outstanding directorial talents. Joining the annual Beijing Music Festival in 2012, she has over the years introduced operas like Don Juan, Written on Skin and Orfeo to the festival. After the ceremony, Zou said that new young talent will bring fresh ideas to the opera world, while the Beijing Music Festival will continue its dialogue between China and the West and introducing young talent to this old art form. Chinese scientists design gene-editing tool using light to kill cancer cellsAbsence at PLA maritime parade will prevent US from learning about Chinese Navy: expertsChinese American organization condemns increasing racial profiling in US Delegation of HUST attends alumni gala in Los AngelesChinese driving Vegas growthHaving fun